SUMMARIZER="H">     

In the transition from winter to spring, hot weather stirs the air and
helps form thunderstorms and tornadoes, violently twisting winds
reaching down from thunderclouds. Tornadoes increase in March and peak
in May, averaging 166 that month, but they can occur any
month. November's average is 23 but last year unusually warm and wet
weather helped trigger 121. Tornadoes are most likely between noon and
sunset and least likely just before sunrise. Typically they are 50
yards wide and travel two miles on the ground, usually heading
northeast, and often come in groups. Tornado deaths are down due to
increased public awareness.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d11"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890403-0123"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="H">     

Tornadoes can occur any month but are more frequent April through
June, between 3 and 6pm. The thunderstorm portion adjacent to large
hail is most likely to produce tornadoes.  Tornadoes mostly travel
northeast but can stand still or spiral erratically. Average speed is
30 mph but can reach 70. Violent tornadoes (less than 2%) have wind
speeds over 200 mph and a 26-mile long path. The longest tornado on
record went 219 miles across Missouri, Illinois and Indiana in March
1925. The largest outbreak was in April 1974 when 148 storms killed
300 people in 13 states over two days.</SUM>

<SUM
