A Wednesday tornado, one of a series in an arc spanning 7 states,
hopped a 25-mile path and carved a 3-mile stretch through Huntsville,
plowing through a school, shopping mall, apartments and rural
areas. It killed 17, injured 463 and left 1,000 homeless. Most dead
were in apartments, stores or cars. Wind, rain, and temperatures
plummeting to the 30s hampered the search for victims. A tornado watch
was issued earlier in the day but the tornado warning did not come
until 4:39pm, when the twister was already tearing up the city,
sounding like a jet at close range and bringing a deluge of
water.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d11"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP891116-0191"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="H">     

Tornadoes and severe thunderstorms killed at least 27 people
Wednesday. The worst hit was Huntsville, Alabama, where 17 people were
killed and 1000 left homeless.  A Kentucky storm believed to be a
tornado cut a mile-long swath of destruction through the town of
Flaherty. Tornadoes were also reported in Mississippi, Georgia, North
and South Carolina, Ohio, Indiana, Pennsylvania, West Virginia,
Maryland, Delaware, New Jersey, and New York. Thunderstorms and high
winds were also wide-spread and caused power outages and other
damage. They caused deaths in Illinois and New York, where a tree
falling on an elementary school roof killed 7 children.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d11"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP900619-0006"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="H">     

1990 is one of the worst tornado years on record, with 726 storms so
far compared to the 6-month average of 482.  Persistent West Coast low
pressure in the upper atmosphere is keeping the jet stream anchored at
a southern latitude, but as summer warms the land, cold air from
Canada will retreat and the jet stream will move north. Studies
indicate tornadoes concentrate in regions for 5-6 years. This year a
Kansas tornado's winds reached 300 mph and 101 tornadoes touched down
in one weekend, leaving 9 dead.  Computers giving access to many data
sources are improving tornado warnings, leading to fewer deaths.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d11"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA070190-0073"
SELECTOR="B"
SUMMARIZER="H">     

World authority Tetsuya Theodore Fujita has studied tornadoes for 42
years. In his University of Chicago lab he creates miniature
tornadoes, with a bottom fan making a swirling motion and a top fan
simulating a low-pressure system's updraft. Miniature versions, like
real tornadoes, are impossible to redirect or squelch. Single, large
thunderstorms are likelier to produce tornadoes than groups of storms,
which compete to rotate "which they all can't do." Most strong
tornadoes are actually 6-7 small ones rotating around a larger
tornado's center. The Fujita Scale ranks tornado strength, with a zero
breaking twigs on trees and a five ripping houses from
foundations.</SUM>
